    {
      "turn_number": 50,
      "role": "persona",
      "type": "response",
      "text": "Yes — there’s a few things I keep circling back to that I didn’t fully say before.\n\nI want providers to see me as a person, not a checklist. After eclampsia, every appointment feels like they’re waiting for me to break again. It would mean everything for someone to sit down, hold my hand through the numbers, and say “we’ll plan this together,” instead of just assigning me a “medium risk” stamp and a schedule. Small gestures — continuity of care, one familiar face, clear explanations — calm the part of me that still wakes up sweating from that hospital room.\n\nPractical barriers matter. Without a car, getting to appointments is exhausting and isolating. Clinics offering flexible hours, telehealth, transportation help, or home visits would change the game.\n\nAlso, I’m terrified about postpartum — not just birth. I worry about another loss, about being alone with a newborn, about going back to work. Trauma-informed counseling, real social support, and honest conversations about safety plus respect for my birth preferences are what I need.\n\nI still hope for a gentle, empowered pregnancy, but I need compassionate partners in care to make that possible.",
      "responding_to_question_id": null,
      "input_tokens": 1827,
      "output_tokens": 503
    }
